This paper discusses the relationship between nominal and structural type systems in object-oriented programming (OOP), which is a topic that falls under the programming languages (PL) sub-category of computer science. Therefore, cs.PL is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the value of nominal typing for designing robust OOP software, which relates to software engineering (SE) and logic in computer science (LO) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the schism between mainstream OOP developers and language designers and PL researchers, which relates to the organizational and societal aspects of computing (OH) and systems and control (SY) sub-categories.
